<stack-static>
    <statement><p><p>
On a Friday afternoon, two earthquakes were recorded in Nakuru at Station A. The first earthquake had magnitude <m>{4}</m>, and the second had magnitude <m>{5}</m>.
</p>

<p>
(a) Find the difference in magnitude between the two earthquakes.
</p>

<p>
<fillin characters="8" name="ans1"/>  
</p>

<p>
(b) Using logarithmic principles, determine how many times more powerful the larger earthquake is compared to the smaller one.
</p>

<p>
<fillin characters="8" name="ans2"/>  
</p></p></statement>
    <solution><p><h3>Worked Solution</h3>

<p>
Step 1: Find the difference in magnitude:
</p>

<p>
<me>
{5} - {4} = {1}
</me>
</p>

<p>
Step 2: Understand the logarithmic scale.
</p>

<p>
Each increase of 1 in magnitude means the intensity becomes 10 times greater.
</p>

<p>
Step 3: Apply the rule:
</p>

<p>
<me>
\text{Intensity ratio} = 10^{1}
</me>
</p>

<p>
<me>
= {10}
</me>
</p>

<p>
Therefore, the larger earthquake is <m>{10}</m> times more powerful than the smaller one.
</p></p></solution>
    <answer><p><m>1</m></p></answer>
    <answer><p><m>10</m></p></answer>
</stack-static>